replies.text: You reminded me there was a time, 3 yrs ago, when this sub promoted this stock and downvoted the naysayers. They IPOed at the right time, when the world was stay at home, and is just one of the many stocks that was lifted during an extraordinary point in history. The same thing is happening with DELL today, they benefitted from stay at home, and benefit from AI buildout today, but they havent done anything special. Its better to invest in companies that grow revenues by their own merit, and not by extraordinary external events.

As a long time pc gamer, this was a hard pass for me when it ipoed. The bulk of the business is components which is very competitive and low margin. Theyve made progress in peripherals but their market is niche mostly gamers and streamers. Compare that to Logitech which does peripherals for that market AND office, work from home, travel. Ok, I have to ask you. Have you played or used their equipment? I invested in Corsair in the past and I sold, but I sold because their equipment is average. Its not the best, but its not terrible. I have used their keyboards, I have a Corsair case for my pc, and I have dabbled a bit with their mice. I even used their ram for my previous pc. I even have a Corsair mouse pad that is their best product to date that I have purchased besides the ram. Nearly all their products serve their purpose but the arent known for their quality and gamers will gravitate towards more expensive or higher quality products after they become more experienced in understanding the market. Corsair products are for first time pc gamers that are trying to stay within budget but still put out a product that feels like a device for a gamer. And as you examine the peripheral market you will find...Razer, Logitech, Zowie, Glorious O and others put out a superior product. I use to not be a razer guy but their products are much higher quality but a higher price point. Though I think Logitech and Razer are beginning to recognize that budget products have a market. Point is that Corsair sort of like eating a Big Mac when one could go to Five Guys or In and Out or a Gourmet Burger place. It does the job in satisfying your appetite, but leaves a lot to be desired. Corsair has not figured out their market, they are just trying to capture all the gamers as a whole and this is why they did well financially with the gamer boom and are now struggling a bit. You should have sold two years ago because this company still has no clear plan forward.

Yes it is. Their hardware architecture for QPU has a competitive advantage.Their ion chain has all-to-all connectivity on the chain which means for each qubit they double the computational space, and a lot of the interesting research coming out utilizing their hardware specifically cites the all-to-all connectivity for providing computational advantage.Their all-to-all connectivity also means they can run any two-gate operation on any part of the chain. The likes of superconductors have to do an operation to get to each other part of the platform to do a two-gate which adds operations and errors.Their ion chain also has exceptionally long coherence time - meaning they can run operations on the chain and maintain the state of the chain for long periods of time. Minutes. Compared to other quantum hardware which is microseconds.Their biggest ding is that their gate speeds are slower compared to other quantum hardware like superconducting, but I am happy from an investor perspective trading slower speed on the machine for much higher quality qubit and usable qubit. It's easier to speed something up that has a good foundation than it is to make a bad foundation good.I have not even touched on what they are doing with networking (which is where a lot of their government contracts are starting) and applications.Now it's just the waiting game for them to monetize this and get to cash-flow-positive and make all the early accumulators wealthy. That's the hope at least.

The difference between quantum and classical computers is quite large, similar to the difference between an x86 processor and an ARM processor. They both can power similar systems but differ as far as OS and software. They also look very dissimilar and the mechanism by which the computing is done is completely different. That being said, it's possible for the two types of computer to communicate and work on the same problem together. That's where we get the idea of hybrid computing, which is what IonQ is pursuing with their Forte Enterprise and Tempo systems. Those two systems are designed to be integrated seamlessly into existing classical data centers. Dell and NVIDIA are some other large supporters of Quantum Hybrid computing, and IonQ happens to be partnered with them for that purpose.To sum things up, yes, quantum computers can function within data centers, but they do require their own operating system, firmware, software, and some types of networking. They are compatible with our existing internet.

Classical GPU-based data centers, like the ones used to train AI models like ChatGPT, use an unsustainable amount of energy. One large data center can use tens of megawatts of power. This power draw not only has massive implications on carbon emissions, the cost of this electricity can be millions of dollars per month. It's so large, in fact, that Microsoft is looking to bring the nuclear power plant at Three Mile Island back online, solely to power AI data centers. That's where quantum comes into play. IonQ's next generation of quantum computers, called IonQ Tempo, will be the first quantum computer to have a greater computational space than classical computers. This is because its 64 algorithmic qubits give it the ability to consider 18,446,744,073,709,551,616 different possibilities simultaneously. This is a whole order of magnitude greater than the world's most powerful supercomputer, Frontier. Frontier consumes over 60 MW of power, while Tempo is expected to consume 2-10 KW. That is 1/10,000th of the power draw, with significantly more power. Tempo is projected to be available in 2025, which will be a major inflection point for quantum computing.

As the QC industry evolves, the single metric investors should be focused on is Useable Computational States of the quantum computer. It rolls up the size and accuracy of problem a QC can solve to a commercially useful degree of accuracy. Media needs to start focusing in on that metric instead of parroting absolute garbage spin.

In general terms, Useable Computational States means the number of USEFUL qubits (n) with the computational states being 2^n.

For comparison, Ionq Forte is 2^36, Quantinuum is 2^21. and at best IBM, Google and Rigetti are 2^17. 

Experimentally, QuEra has demonstrated 2^48 with neutral atoms but could face scaling issues like the superconducting modality. IONQ’s Tempo will be 2^64 which surpasses the largest super computer in the world (Fortier).

Pull out your calculator to fully appreciate the differences in the size of problems these quantum computers can handle. LETS GET EVERYONE ON THE SAME PAGE!

Summary… (note 3of3) pending approval.

*Neutral atoms modality has be a recent newcomer. Most notable is QuEra’s Aquila QC that has reported to have created 48 logical qubits out of 256 neutral atoms. The outstanding question is can they scale this tech with short coherence times (approx 1 second), fidelities in the 99.5% range, and a lack of true all to all connectivity. 

Feel free to copy and paste to other platforms as I welcome the vetting of this assessment. 

Remember, many major QC companies want investors to be confused, because frankly, they are losing the race.

3. Coherence Time - This is the amount of time the qubits remain in a state of entanglement with each other. The longer the coherence time the greater the ability to scale the quantum computer. Trapped ion QC’s (Ionq, Quantinuum) can maintain coherence for well over 1 minute. Other modalities are generally one second or under.

For universal quantum advantage you want high fidelity (99.9%+) two gate fidelities that have all to all connectivity with each other that maintains long coherence times. For context, IONQ’s AQ64 Tempo will be able to accurately explore a computational space that is 10.8x that of the worlds largest super computer (Frontier) on a standard household power supply.

2. Qubit Fidelity- Measures how accurately the entangled quantum state matches the ideal state (classical answer). The ideal state is a logical qubit with 99.999%+ two-gate fidelity. Both Ionq and Quantinuum have 99.9%+ fidelities (useable qubits), which at that level of accuracy, opens up almost all types of use cases. Most other modalities achieve a fidelity of at best 99.5% with most of their qubits going to error correction with no fundamental fix to their fidelity issue insight. They are facing logarithmic qubit growth to be able to scale. Ionq believes they will achieve logical qubit fidelity on their useable qubits(AQ) in 2025. Quantinuum just announce that by using error correction they created 12 logical qubits. It’s interesting, but not that useful at such a small computational space. 

2/3

The below is not financial advice. It is an attempt to make some general sense of the QC landscape. Happy to be corrected on any inaccuracies. 

Anyone researching quantum computing needs to understand three main things in general order of importance:

1. Computational Space - It is the computational size of the problem the quantum computer can handle. It is directly tied to i) the number of useable qubits (see below) and ii) the degree of connectivity between them. Quantinuum H2 is 2^21, Ionq Forte Enterprise is 2^36 and IONQ’s soon to be announced Tempo is 2^64. Use your calculator to calculate these exponents. You will quickly find out why Ionq is the leader. I don’t mention other fidelities b/c they don’t report this metric give their challenges with error correction which severely limits their computational space. Neutral atoms (ie QuEra) is an exception of which I cover below.

This is the last time I'm gonna explain this. 

We, as retail investors, have chosen to invest in IonQ because of its wonderful, wealth creating potential. We took on a lot of risk by placing our bet on the company to deliver us returns. Some of us may have had unrealistic time-frames in mind. Startup tech companies, especially ones that are doing things that have never been done before, take YEARS to reach profitability. It's fun and easy to ride the waves of volatility, making money on the uptrends. It's also psychologically distressing when we see our investment lose value. 

The economic forces that control share prices are larger than any one of us retail investors. Therefore it either takes a massive change in sentiment or corroboration at scale for retail investors to sway a share price. Thus, 99.9% of the price changes are wholly created by money managers and large banks. This is who we call "Wall Street," I need not explain why. 

Wall Street as a whole is a momentum player. It is taught in business schools around the world that businesses need to not only have the ability but also the propensity to increase stockholders' equity over time. This requires a historical, consistent, positively growing trend in net income. A company like IonQ that has not yet proven such a trend is possible in a given sector is undesirable to Wall Street. They won't touch it until it is more guaranteed that it can maximize shareholder value. 

Another important thing to realize is that Wall Street bankers are just like you and I. They have a job, and they earn money from this job, and in the face of limitless scarcity, more money is better to have. The way that money managers make the most cash for themselves is by generating the largest return possible each year. This is the primary reason that IonQ is struggling. It's not set to generate a net income for at least 2 more years. Therefore there isn't any real reason for the share price to take off until then, so for now it's just a risky place to have cash. It may go up, or it may go down. The money managers aren't willing to take this risk; they want an investment more certain to help bolster their year-end bonuses. So, they take less risk and increase the turnover rate of their portfolios. They ride the upward momentum on exciting industries like AI. 

I believe quantum computing will follow in the footsteps of AI, but it's a waiting game at this point. It'll take a lot of patience and mental fortitude to get there, but eventually Wall Street will want to ride the momentum of innovation that QC brings. This alone is enough for me to take the risk in hopes of being along for the ride. 

As IonQ's fundamentals only get better and better, the share price is remaining constant, even struggling to hold previous support levels. If this isn't the most bullish signal in the world, I don't know what is.

Topological states will be the next great leap in quantum computing. Non-albelian Anyons are quasi particles that exist in a two dimensional topological state resistant to the laws of thermodynamics (noise that leads to decoherence) in the three dimensional state. Here's what I understand about the different qubit modalities. 

As I'm sure you know, IonQ uses a trapped-ion architecture. I'm confident that this is the best modality, for a number of reasons. I'll use superconducting qubits as a comparison since they're the most popular modality. SC computers require entire buildings to be put up, with massive dampeners and cooling loops to help the system operate. IonQ's Forte Enterprise can be directly integrated into any existing data center. This is currently being done in Basel Switzerland. Back to the cooling, superconducting qubits need to be cooled to near absolute zero to achieve quantum properties. This requires a costly and sensitive liquid helium cooling loop. Trapped Ion systems operate at room temperature since the cooling is done internally by lasers. Superconducting qubits are also very sensitive to vibrations. A researcher walking in proximity to a superconducting system can cause the system to lose coherence and fail whatever operation is being performed. Trapped Ion systems are not nearly as sensitive to vibration, since the ions are suspended in a vacuum and held into place, again by lasers. Then there's the idea of coherence time: the duration that a quantum computer can focus on any given problem. Superconducting systems' coherence times are measured in the milliseconds; they're short bursts of coherence, so complex problems are more difficult on those systems. IonQ's machines have coherence times on the order of 10 minutes. This opens up a whole new realm of possibilities for what type of problems can be completed. Then there's the gate fidelity. Superconducting qubits are asymmetrical; they have different masses and sizes and therefore have greater difficulty communicating, which gives a higher gate fidelity. Think of that like an accuracy rating. SC qubit companies typically state their fidelity in terms of "average two-qubit gate fidelity." I'll explain the significance of that in a second. Trapped ion systems typically have much higher fidelity, IonQ has achieved 99.999% with their barium platform on which AQ64 Tempo will be based. IonQ chooses to use "All-to-All gate fidelity" as opposed to average 2-qubit. They believe that all-to-all is a more standardized and useful metric than average 2-qubit, since it accounts for communication between all qubits simultaneously, which is where superconducting modalities lack. Trapped ions' list of advantages goes on, these were just some that I remembered off the top of my head.

Frontier consumes 21MW’s of power. That is equal to the power required by 15,000 single family homes. Tempo can perform its operation on a single standard house power supply. 

Time to solution and power requirement are the two fundamental keys to quantum advantage.

This paper, scan the name, is a very useful corrective on the real state of AI.  AI/LLM's are very useful, of course, for many things.  Used properly they are a great tool for productivity.  But they lack the simplest real logic and reasoning and it's not easily fixable.  Automating real human intelligence is a very hard problem.  From the paper: "The original problem formulation, of which we will present various versions in our investigation is as following: "Alice has N brothers and she also has M sisters. How many sisters does Alice’s brother have?". The problem features a fictional female person (as hinted by the "she" pronoun) called Alice, providing clear statements about her number of brothers and sisters, and asking a clear question to determine the number of sisters a brother of Alice has. The problem has a light quiz style and is arguably no challenge for most adult humans and probably to some extent even not a hard problem to solve via common sense reasoning if posed to children above certain age."  But LLM's can't do it."Alice in Wonderland: Simple Tasks Showing Complete Reasoning Breakdown in State-Of-the-Art Large Language Models"

Booking is generally a contract signed by a buyer and indicator of future revenue.  In the case of the $4-5M booking in Q2 for the design of the system for ARLIS, that likely will be complete by thge end of this fiscal year and subsequently be recognized as revenue when complete.  Bookings for the blance of the contract will be recognized in Q3 or Q4 this year assuming the design phase is complete.  Bookings this year may impact revenue this year or in subsequent years depending on when revenue is recognized.  Systems take longer to deliver than design, etc.  As I recall ARLIS also calls for "service' which could involve revenue recognition over several ears.  Chapman did say that IONQ is now recognizing revenue for past bookings (I am guessing primarily Basel and Air Force systems).

Bookings are more of a reservation, think booking a hotel room. No payment is received, so bookings don't need to be accounted for as unearned revenue. Bookings are important for IonQ as only one client can use a system at a time. They also account for system sales as bookings because they figure larger clients will buy a whole system instead of waiting to access one of the cloud systems. This is why only about 10% of the bookings guidance for this year has been realized.

IBM's coherence time is in the miliseconds, while IonQ's is in the minutes. That has a lot of implications for the size and complexity of computations the systems can do. Also, qubit count isn't everything. Gate fidelity sets a limit on the computational capacity of a system, regardless of qubit count. That's why IonQ uses the #AQ metric, because it standardizes the power of a quantum computer and accounts for the different factors that determine the computational capacity. The reason other companies don't use #AQ is because they don't want people to know how much slower their systems are than IonQ. Another advantage that IonQ has is the system's construction. IBM's systems require infrastructure that costs hundreds of millions on top of the system cost that is already $50+ million. They also need to be cooled by liquid helium for their synthetic superconducting qubits to obtain quantum properties. IonQ's systems cost $10 million total, don't require any changes to infrastructure, and can run at room temperature. Based on that information, it should be clear who number one is. If it's not clear to you, it's best to not invest in businesses you don't fully understand.
My point is there is a lot of way to approach quantum computing. I think in this case IBM is number one, but when it come to Fidelity ionq is the best. What’s your opinion guys?
